  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). It is universally recognized as a serious criminal offense because it undermines the integrity of financial systems, facilitates corruption, organized crime, and terrorism, and distorts economies.\n\nNearly all countries have enacted laws and regulations to combat money laundering, often in compliance with international standards set by organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), the United Nations, and the International Monetary Fund (IMF). These laws typically require financial institutions and other entities to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures, such as customer due diligence, reporting suspicious activities, and maintaining records.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is unequivocally against the law in virtually every jurisdiction, and there is widespread international agreement on the importance of combating it.",
